{"title_page": "Corran Ferry", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{coord|56|43|21|N|5|14|34.07|W|region:GB|display=title}}\nThe '''Corran Ferry''' crosses [[Loch Linnhe]] at the Corran Narrows, south of [[Fort William, Scotland]].\n[[File:Corran Ferry.JPG|thumb|''The Corran'' landing at [[Ardgour]]]]\n==Description==\nOperated by [[Highland (council area)|Highland Council]], the Corran Ferry is one of few remaining mainland vehicle ferries in Scotland.<ref name=\"undisc\">{{cite web| url=http://www.undiscoveredscotland.co.uk/corran/corranferry/index.html| title=Corran Ferry| publisher=Undiscovered Scotland| accessdate=19 September 2009}}</ref> The route crosses [[Loch Linnhe]] from [[Nether Lochaber]] to [[Ardgour]],<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lochabertransport.org.uk/TransportinLochaber/PublicTransport/Ferries/CorranFerry.aspx| title=Corran Ferry| publisher=Lochaber Transport Forum| accessdate=8 August 2010}}</ref> at the Corran Narrows, {{convert|9|mi|km|0}} south of [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]]. \n\nIt was noted for the unusual sign \"This is not the Ballachulish Ferry\", placed there to avoid confusion with the nearby ferry at [[Ballachulish]] which crossed [[Loch Leven (Highlands)|Loch Leven]] until being replaced by the [[Ballachulish Bridge]] in early 1976.\n\nThe route lies on one of the ancient [[Drovers' road|drove routes]] from the Hebrides to the cattle markets in Central Scotland.<ref name=\"undisc\"/> Today, the ferry is a crucial link between the main [[A82 road]] (serving [[Inverness]], [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]], and [[Glasgow]]) with the otherwise extremely remote [[Morvern]] and [[Ardnamurchan]] peninsulas. Use of the ferry saves over an hour from the land route between Ardgour and Corran (which would involve use of the [[A861 road|A861]] and the [[A830 road|A830]]).\n\nServices are fairly frequent, with ferries operating every 20 to 30 minutes seven days a week. Travel on foot is free, but [[roll-on/roll-off|bringing a passenger vehicle]] costs \u00a38.50\n\n\nFrom the Ardgour side, there are roadway connections to [[Lochaline]], {{convert|31|mi|km|0}} to the southwest, and to [[Kilchoan]], {{convert|44|mi|km|0}} to the west; both of these locations are linked by [[Caledonian MacBrayne]] ferries to points on the [[Isle of Mull]], respectively [[Fishnish]] and [[Tobermory, Mull|Tobermory]].\n\nClose to the Ardgour side are Corran Lighthouse and the Ardgour Inn.\n\n==Ferries==\nThere has been a ferry at the site for centuries.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ambaile.org.uk/en/search/data?type_id=3&field,DC_SPATIAL_LOCATION,substring,string=Corran| title=Memories of Corran Ferry| format=audio| publisher=Am Baile| accessdate=19 September 2009}}</ref> The ''North Argyll'', a [[Ferry#Turntable_ferry|turntable ferry]], was on the route in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.scran.ac.uk/database/record.php?usi=000-000-463-728-C&scache=17o9h3jeff&searchdb=scran| title=The Corran Ferry, Ardgour, Argyll| date=c. 1930s| publisher=Scran/RCAHMS| accessdate=19 September 2009}}</ref> Her deck rotated to allow one car to drive easily onto the slipway.\n\nThe {{MV|Maid of Glencoul||2}}, launched in 1976 in Ardrossan, spent her early years operating between [[Kylesku]] and Kylestrome in the far north west of Scotland. She was displaced when the [[Kylesku#Bridge|Kylesku Bridge]] opened in 1984.<ref name=\"undisc\"/> She continues as the backup ferry on the route.\n\nThe ''Rosehaugh'' was displaced from the [[Kessock Ferry]] in 1982 by the opening of the [[Kessock Bridge]].<ref name=\"undisc\"/> She was retired in 2001 after 32 years in service on various routes across the Highlands. \n\nThe ''Corran'' replaced the ''Rosehaugh'' in late 2001. She was built in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] for \u00a32.9 million and brought additional capacity to the crossing.<ref name=\"undisc\"/>\n\n==Footnotes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Ferry transport in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Transport in Highland (council area)]]\n[[Category:Lochaber]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2017}}\n{{coord|56|43|21|N|5|14|34.07|W|region:GB|display=title}}\nThe '''Corran Ferry''' crosses [[Loch Linnhe]] at the Corran Narrows, south of [[Fort William, Scotland]].\n[[File:Corran Ferry.JPG|thumb|''The Corran'' landing at [[Ardgour]]]]\n==Description==\nOperated by [[Highland (council area)|Highland Council]], the Corran Ferry is one of few remaining mainland vehicle ferries in Scotland.<ref name=\"undisc\">{{cite web| url=http://www.undiscoveredscotland.co.uk/corran/corranferry/index.html| title=Corran Ferry| publisher=Undiscovered Scotland| accessdate=19 September 2009}}</ref> The route crosses [[Loch Linnhe]] from Nether Lochaber to Ardgour,<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.lochabertransport.org.uk/TransportinLochaber/PublicTransport/Ferries/CorranFerry.aspx| title=Corran Ferry| publisher=Lochaber Transport Forum| accessdate=8 August 2010}}</ref> at the Corran Narrows, {{convert|9|mi|km|0}} south of [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]]. \n\nIt was noted for the unusual sign \"This is not the Ballachulish Ferry\", placed there to avoid confusion with the nearby ferry at [[Ballachulish]] which crossed [[Loch Leven (Highlands)|Loch Leven]] until being replaced by the [[Ballachulish Bridge]] in early 1976.\n\nThe route lies on one of the ancient [[Drovers' road|drove routes]] from the Hebrides to the cattle markets in Central Scotland.<ref name=\"undisc\"/> Today, the ferry is a crucial link between the main [[A82 road]] (serving [[Inverness]], [[Fort William, Scotland|Fort William]], and [[Glasgow]]) with the otherwise extremely remote [[Morvern]] and [[Ardnamurchan]] peninsulas. Use of the ferry saves over an hour from the land route between Ardgour and Corran (which would involve use of the [[A861 road|A861]] and the [[A830 road|A830]]).\n\nServices are fairly frequent, with ferries operating every 20 to 30 minutes seven days a week. Travel on foot is free, but [[roll-on/roll-off|bringing a passenger vehicle]] costs \u00a38.50\n\n\nFrom the Ardgour side, there are roadway connections to [[Lochaline]], {{convert|31|mi|km|0}} to the southwest, and to [[Kilchoan]], {{convert|44|mi|km|0}} to the west; both of these locations are linked by [[Caledonian MacBrayne]] ferries to points on the [[Isle of Mull]], respectively [[Fishnish]] and [[Tobermory, Mull|Tobermory]].\n\nClose to the Ardgour side are Corran Lighthouse and the Ardgour Inn.\n\n==Ferries==\nThere has been a ferry at the site for centuries.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.ambaile.org.uk/en/search/data?type_id=3&field,DC_SPATIAL_LOCATION,substring,string=Corran| title=Memories of Corran Ferry| format=audio| publisher=Am Baile| accessdate=19 September 2009}}</ref> The ''North Argyll'', a [[Ferry#Turntable_ferry|turntable ferry]], was on the route in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.scran.ac.uk/database/record.php?usi=000-000-463-728-C&scache=17o9h3jeff&searchdb=scran| title=The Corran Ferry, Ardgour, Argyll| date=c. 1930s| publisher=Scran/RCAHMS| accessdate=19 September 2009}}</ref> Her deck rotated to allow one car to drive easily onto the slipway.\n\nThe {{MV|Maid of Glencoul||2}}, launched in 1976 in Ardrossan, spent her early years operating between [[Kylesku]] and Kylestrome in the far north west of Scotland. She was displaced when the [[Kylesku#Bridge|Kylesku Bridge]] opened in 1984.<ref name=\"undisc\"/> She continues as the backup ferry on the route.\n\nThe ''Rosehaugh'' was displaced from the [[Kessock Ferry]] in 1982 by the opening of the [[Kessock Bridge]].<ref name=\"undisc\"/> She was retired in 2001 after 32 years in service on various routes across the Highlands. \n\nThe ''Corran'' replaced the ''Rosehaugh'' in late 2001. She was built in [[Kingston upon Hull|Hull]] for \u00a32.9 million and brought additional capacity to the crossing.<ref name=\"undisc\"/>\n\n