{"title_page": "Robert Collier, 2nd Baron Monkswell", "text_new": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Monkswell\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Robert Collier.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption =Lord Monkswell, 1885\n| order1 = [[Under-Secretary of State for War]]\n| term_start1 = 5 January 1895\n| term_end1 = 21 June 1895\n| monarch1 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]]\n| predecessor1 = [[William Mansfield, 1st Viscount Sandhurst|The Lord Sandhurst]]\n| successor1 = [[St John Brodrick, 1st Earl of Midleton|Hon. St John Brodrick]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|26 January 1845}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death-date and age|22 December 1909|26 January 1845}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]\n| alma_mater =\n| spouse = Mary Josephine Hardcastle <br>(d. 1930)\n}}\n\n'''Robert Collier, 2nd Baron Monkswell''' (26 March 1845 \u2013 22 December 1909), was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician. He was briefly [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] under [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]] in 1895. As a young man, he was a [[first-class cricket]]er active from 1866 to 1867. He was born and died in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]].\n\n==Background==\nMonkswell was the eldest son of [[Robert Collier, 1st Baron Monkswell]], and his wife Isabella Rose, daughter of William Rose. The artist [[John Collier (Pre-Raphaelite painter)|John Collier]] was his younger brother.<ref name=\"cracroft\">[http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1066.htm cracroftspeerage.co.uk Monkswell, Baron (UK, 1885)]</ref>\n\n==Cricket career==\nMonkswell did not succeed to his title until 1886 and so was known as Robert Collier during his cricket career. He appeared for [[Cambridge Town Club]] (''aka'' Cambridgeshire) in three first-class matches, scoring 33 [[run (cricket)|runs]] with a highest score of 14.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/28/28638/28638.html Robert Collier at CricketArchive]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Robert Collier, 2nd Baron Monkswell (1845-1909), photographed on 28 July 1902.jpg|thumb|2nd Baron Monkswell, photographed on 28 July 1902.]]\nLord Monkswell entered the [[House of Lords]] on his father's death in 1886, and later served in the [[Liberal Government 1892-1895|Liberal administrations]] of [[William Ewart Gladstone]] and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]] as a [[Lord-in-waiting]] from 1892<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26327 |date=20 September 1892 |page=4329 }}</ref> to 1895<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26595 |date=5 February 1895 |page=683 }}</ref> and as [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] from January to June 1895. He was also a member of the [[London County Council]] for the [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive Party]], and served as Vice-Chairman 1902\u201303, and [[List of chairmen of the London County Council|Chairman]] 1903\u201304.\n\n==Family==\nLord Monkswell married Mary Josephine Hardcastle, daughter of [[Joseph Hardcastle (politician)|Joseph Hardcastle]], in 1873. He died in December 1909, aged 64, and was succeeded in the barony by his eldest son [[Robert Collier, 3rd Baron Monkswell|Robert]]. Lady Monkswell died in May 1930.<ref name=\"cracroft\"/>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Monkswell Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Argent on a chevron Azure between in chief two demi-unicorns courant and in base an elephant's head erased Gules three oak branches slipped leaved and fructed Or.\n|crest = A demiman affronttee Proper holding in the dexter hand an oak branch slipped and leaved Proper fructed Or and resting the sinister hand on an escutcheon Azure charged with two keys saltirewise Or.\n|supporters = Two druids vested Argent wreathed about the temples with laurel leaves Vert each resting the exterior hand on an escutcheon Azure charged with a balance suspended Or.\n|motto = Persevere <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=200}}</ref>}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] | before=[[Charles Marsham, 4th Earl of Romney|The Earl of Romney]] | after=[[Granville Leveson-Gower, 3rd Earl Granville|The Earl Granville]] | years=1892&ndash;1895}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Under-Secretary of State for War]] | before=[[William Mansfield, 1st Viscount Sandhurst|The Lord Sandhurst]] | after=[[St John Brodrick, 1st Earl of Midleton|Hon. St John Brodrick]] | years=January\u2013June 1895}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andrew Mitchell Torrance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of chairmen of the London County Council|Chairman of the London County Council]]|years=1903 &ndash; 1904}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sir John Benn, 1st Baronet|John Benn]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Baron Monkswell]] | before=[[Robert Collier, 1st Baron Monkswell|Robert Monkswell]] | after=[[Robert Collier, 3rd Baron Monkswell|Robert Collier]] | years=1886&ndash;1909 }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monkswell, Robert Collier, 2nd Baron}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cambridge Town Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (London) politicians]]\n\n\n{{england-cricket-bio-1840s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n| name = The Lord Monkswell\n| honorific-suffix =\n| image = Robert Collier.jpg\n| imagesize =\n| caption =Lord Monkswell, 1885\n| order1 = [[Under-Secretary of State for War]]\n| term_start1 = 5 January 1895\n| term_end1 = 21 June 1895\n| monarch1 = [[Victoria of the United Kingdom|Victoria]]\n| primeminister1 = [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]]\n| predecessor1 = [[William Mansfield, 1st Viscount Sandhurst|The Lord Sandhurst]]\n| successor1 = [[St John Brodrick, 1st Earl of Midleton|Hon. St John Brodrick]]\n| birth_date = {{birth-date|26 January 1845}}\n| birth_place =\n| death_date = {{death-date and age|22 December 1909|26 January 1845}}\n| death_place =\n| nationality = [[British people|British]]\n| party = [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]]\n| alma_mater =\n| spouse = Mary Josephine Hardcastle <br>(d. 1930)\n}}\n\n'''Robert Collier, 2nd Baron Monkswell''' (26 March 1845 \u2013 22 December 1909), was a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal]] politician. He was briefly [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] under [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|The Earl of Rosebery]] in 1895. As a young man, he was a [[first-class cricket]]er active from 1866 to 1867. He was born and died in [[Chelsea, London|Chelsea]].\n\n==Background==\nMonkswell was the eldest son of [[Robert Collier, 1st Baron Monkswell]], and his wife Isabella Rose, daughter of William Rose. The artist [[John Collier (Pre-Raphaelite painter)|John Collier]] was his younger brother.<ref name=\"cracroft\">[http://www.cracroftspeerage.co.uk/online/content/index1066.htm cracroftspeerage.co.uk Monkswell, Baron (UK, 1885)]</ref>\n\n==Cricket career==\nMonkswell did not succeed to his title until 1886 and so was known as Robert Collier during his cricket career. He appeared for [[Cambridge Town Club]] (''aka'' Cambridgeshire) in three first-class matches, scoring 33 [[run (cricket)|runs]] with a highest score of 14.<ref>[https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/28/28638/28638.html Robert Collier at CricketArchive]</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n[[File:Robert Collier, 2nd Baron Monkswell (1845-1909), photographed on 28 July 1902.jpg|thumb|2nd Baron Monkswell, photographed on 28 July 1902.]]\nLord Monkswell entered the [[House of Lords]] on his father's death in 1886, and later served in the [[Liberal Government 1892-1895|Liberal administrations]] of [[William Ewart Gladstone]] and [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]] as a [[Lord-in-waiting]] from 1892<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26327 |date=20 September 1892 |page=4329 }}</ref> to 1895<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=26595 |date=5 February 1895 |page=683 }}</ref> and as [[Under-Secretary of State for War]] from January to June 1895. He was also a member of the [[London County Council]] for the [[Progressive Party (London)|Progressive Party]], and served as Vice-Chairman 1902-03, and [[List of chairmen of the London County Council|Chairman]] 1903-04.\n\n==Family==\nLord Monkswell married Mary Josephine Hardcastle, daughter of [[Joseph Hardcastle (politician)|Joseph Hardcastle]], in 1873. He died in December 1909, aged 64, and was succeeded in the barony by his eldest son [[Robert Collier, 3rd Baron Monkswell|Robert]]. Lady Monkswell died in May 1930.<ref name=\"cracroft\"/>\n\n==Arms==\n{{Infobox COA wide\n|image=[[File:Coronet of a British Baron.svg|centre|150px]][[File:Monkswell Escutcheon.png|centre|200px]]\n|escutcheon = Argent on a chevron Azure between in chief two demi-unicorns courant and in base an elephant's head erased Gules three oak branches slipped leaved and fructed Or.\n|crest = A demiman affronttee Proper holding in the dexter hand an oak branch slipped and leaved Proper fructed Or and resting the sinister hand on an escutcheon Azure charged with two keys saltirewise Or.\n|supporters = Two druids vested Argent wreathed about the temples with laurel leaves Vert each resting the exterior hand on an escutcheon Azure charged with a balance suspended Or.\n|motto = Persevere <ref>{{cite book|title=Debrett's Peerage |date=200}}</ref>}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{S-off}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] | before=[[Charles Marsham, 4th Earl of Romney|The Earl of Romney]] | after=[[Granville Leveson-Gower, 3rd Earl Granville|The Earl Granville]] | years=1892&ndash;1895}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Under-Secretary of State for War]] | before=[[William Mansfield, 1st Viscount Sandhurst|The Lord Sandhurst]] | after=[[St John Brodrick, 1st Earl of Midleton|Hon. St John Brodrick]] | years=January\u2013June 1895}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Andrew Mitchell Torrance]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of chairmen of the London County Council|Chairman of the London County Council]]|years=1903 &ndash; 1904}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Sir John Benn, 1st Baronet|John Benn]]}}\n{{S-reg|uk}}\n{{Succession box | title=[[Baron Monkswell]] | before=[[Robert Collier, 1st Baron Monkswell|Robert Monkswell]] | after=[[Robert Collier, 3rd Baron Monkswell|Robert Collier]] | years=1886&ndash;1909 }}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2012}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monkswell, Robert Collier, 2nd Baron}}\n[[Category:1845 births]]\n[[Category:1909 deaths]]\n[[Category:English cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cambridge Town Club cricketers]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:Members of London County Council]]\n[[Category:Progressive Party (London) politicians]]\n\n\n{{england-cricket-bio-1840s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePolitical career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1902-03 \u2192 1902\u201303 (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Collier,_2nd_Baron_Monkswell"}
{"title_page": "Thomas Denman, 3rd Baron Denman", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Governor-General\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Denman\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=|GCMG|KCVO|PC}}\n|image=Lord Denman.jpg\n|order=5th\n|office=Governor-General of Australia\n|term_start=31 July 1911\n|term_end=18 May 1914\n|monarch=[[George V]]\n|primeminister    = [[Andrew Fisher]]<br/>[[Joseph Cook]]\n|predecessor=[[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|Lord Dudley]]\n|successor=[[Ronald Munro Ferguson, 1st Viscount Novar|Sir Ronald Munro Ferguson]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|1874|11|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[London]], England\n|death_date={{death date and age|1954|6|24|1874|11|16|df=y}}\n|death_place=[[Hove]], [[Sussex]], England\n|spouse={{Marriage|[[Gertrude Denman, Baroness Denman|Gertrude Pearson]]|1913|1954|reason=her death}}\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Denman, 3rd Baron Denman''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCMG|KCVO|PC}} (16 November 1874 \u2013 24 June 1954), was a British aristocrat and politician who served as the [[List of Governors-General of Australia|fifth Governor-General of Australia]], in office from 1911 to 1914.\n\nDenman was born into the English nobility, inheriting his title at the age of 19 from a great-uncle. He attended the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]], and served in the [[Second Boer War]]. Denman sat with the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] in the [[House of Lords]], and was made a [[Lord-in-waiting]] in 1905 and [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats#Liberal Party|Chief Whip]] in 1907. He was appointed to the governor-generalship at the age of 36, and remains the youngest person to have held the position. Denman and his young family were immensely popular with the general public, and he enjoyed friendly relations with Prime Minister [[Andrew Fisher]], with whom he shared many similar political opinions. However, he suffered from ill health and returned to England after less than three years as governor-general. Denman never again held public office, but remained active in the House of Lords and briefly commanded a unit in the First World War.\n\n==Early life and military career==\nDenman was born in [[London]] on 16 November 1874, the son of Richard Denman and the former Helen Mary McMicking. His father was the grandson of [[Thomas Denman, 1st Baron Denman]], who was [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Lord Chief Justice]] from 1832 to 1850. Denman was the second of three children, and the oldest son. His younger brother, [[Richard Denman|Sir Richard Denman]], was also a Liberal Party politician.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas Denman, 3rd Baron Denman of Dovedale|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p13233.htm#i132327|publisher=thepeerage.com|accessdate=5 April 2011|date=6 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDenman's parents divorced in 1878. His father did not remarry, and died in 1883 when his son was eight.<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p2357.htm#i23562 Hon. Richard Denman]</ref> However, his mother remarried twice \u2013 in 1879 to James Walker (annulled due to desertion), and then in 1888 to [[Henry Primrose]] (a civil servant and cousin of [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]]).<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p2951.htm Helen Mary McMicking]</ref>\n\nIn 1894, aged 19, Denman succeeded [[Thomas Aitchison-Denman, 2nd Baron Denman|his great-uncle]] as Baron Denman; he took his seat in the [[House of Lords]] on his 21st birthday. He intended a military career and was a graduate of the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]. Denman began his career in the [[Royal Scots]], where he was promoted to [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 4 March 1896, but resigned in May 1899 and was placed in the Reserve. Returning to active service following the outbreak of the [[Second Boer War]], he was on 3 February 1900 commissioned as a lieutenant of the 11th Battalion, [[Imperial Yeomanry]],<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27160 |page=692 |date=2 February 1900}}</ref> and left [[Liverpool]] for [[South Africa]] on the [[SS Cymric|SS ''Cymric'']] in March 1900.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The War - Embarcation of Troops|day_of_week=Thursday |date=1 March 1900 |page_number=7 |issue=36078| }}</ref> He was promoted to [[Captain (BARM)|captain]] in the battalion on 18 July 1900, and the following year was appointed a captain in the [[Middlesex Yeomanry|Middlesex (Duke of Cambridge's Hussars) Imperial Yeomanry]], followed by a promotion to [[Major (British Army)|major]] on 30 April 1902.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27429 |page=2866 |date=29 April 1902}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nDenman had little money until 1903, when he married [[Gertrude Denman, Baroness Denman|Gertrude Pearson]], daughter of the wealthy industrialist [[Weetman Pearson, 1st Viscount Cowdray|Weetman Pearson]] (later Viscount Cowdray). He was then able to devote his time to public life and served in the [[Liberal Government 1905-1915|Liberal administrations]] of Sir [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman]] and [[H. H. Asquith]] as a [[Lord-in-waiting]] (government whip in the House of Lords) from 1905 to 1907 and as [[Captain of the Honourable Corps of Gentlemen-at-Arms]] (government chief whip in the House of Lords) between 1907 and 1911. He was sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1907.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28050 |date=13 August 1907 |page=5523}}</ref> In 1909, he was appointed to the [[Royal Victorian Order]] as a Knight Commander.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28251 |date=17 May 1909 |page=3753 |supp=y}}</ref> In 1911, [[Lewis Harcourt, 1st Viscount Harcourt|Lord Harcourt]], the [[Secretary of State for the Colonies|Colonial Secretary]], offered Denman the post of [[Governor-General of Australia]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28483 |date=7 April 1911 |page=2802}}</ref> apparently to get him out of domestic politics.<ref name=adb>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography |last= Cunneen |first= Chris |year=1981 |id=A080304b |title= Denman, Thomas [Baron Denman] (1874\u20131954) |accessdate=30 April 2008 }}</ref> In the [[1911 Coronation Honours]], Lord Denman was appointed to the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] as a Knight Grand Cross.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28505 |date=16 June 1911 |page=4593 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Governor-General==\n[[Image:Aussie pm Andrew Fisher cropped from naming of Canberra.JPG|left|thumb|Denman, to the left of [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] Prime Minister [[Andrew Fisher]], at the naming of [[Canberra]] in 1913.]]\n[[File:Laying of the foundation stone of the Commencement Column, Canberra.jpg|left|thumb|Lord and Lady Denman, [[King O'Malley]] and Andrew Fisher at the official ceremony on Capitol Hill to mark the commencement of work on the city of Canberra, 12 March 1913]]\n[[File:The cadets being inspected by the Governor-General 12 March 1913.jpg|thumb|The cadets being inspected by the Governor-General on 12 March 1913, at the Canberra naming ceremony]]\nThe Denmans arrived in Melbourne on 31 July 1911.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/denman-thomas-5956|title = Denman, Thomas (1874\u20131954)|date = 1981|accessdate = 1 April 2015|website = Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher = Melbourne University Press|last = Cunneen|first = Chris}}</ref> They found [[Andrew Fisher]]'s [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] government firmly in control. As the most politically liberal Governor-General yet appointed, he got on well with the Labor ministers, and his modesty and generosity with his father-in-law's money made him popular with the public.  In October 1912, the [[Premiers of New South Wales|New South Wales Premier]], [[James McGowen]] \"evicted\" him from [[Government House, Sydney]]. On 12 March 1913, he inaugurated the site of the future national capital and Lady Denman formally announced its name, [[Canberra]].<ref name=adb/> On 12 March 2013, his great-nephew, the 6th Baron Denman and his wife attended celebrations in Canberra commemorating the centenary of the naming of the city.<ref>[http://www.canberratimes.com.au/act-news/100-years-on-the-denmans-pay-visit-to-scene-of-ancestors-public-office-20130310-2fukr.html ''Canberra Times'', 11 March 2013]</ref>\n\nBut Denman found that he had less real political influence than any previous Governor-General. As Australia, along with the other [[dominion]]s, achieved political maturity, its Prime Minister communicated directly with his British counterpart, cutting the Colonial Secretary and the Governor-General out of the loop. The appointment of an Australian High Commissioner in London further reduced the Governor-General's diplomatic role.\n\nIn May 1913 the Labor government was unexpectedly defeated at a [[1913 Australian federal election|general election]] by [[Joseph Cook]]'s [[Commonwealth Liberal Party|Liberals]]. But Labor retained control of the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] and was determined to frustrate Cook's government at every turn. By early 1914 it was clear that a [[constitutional crisis]] was developing.  Denman was in poor health{{mdash}}that he was allergic to Australia's national flower, the wattle, did not help{{mdash}}and his marriage was suffering from his wife's unhappiness at being so far from home. He felt he lacked the strength to deal with the political situation, and in May 1914 he resigned.<ref name=adb/>\n\nThe [[Denman Glacier]] in eastern [[Antarctica]] was named after Denman by [[Sir Douglas Mawson]]. It had been discovered by the [[Australasian Antarctic Expedition]] of 1911\u201314.\n\n==Later years==\nWith the outbreak of the [[World War I|Great War]], Denman commanded a [[Yeomanry]] regiment from 1914 until 1915. He was appointed [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)#Ceremonial_usage|Honorary Colonel]] of the [[2nd Cavalry Divisional Signals (Middlesex Yeomanry)]] on 11 April 1923.<ref>''Army List''.</ref> He remained loyal to [[H. H. Asquith|Asquith]] and the Liberals and so did not hold office again, leading a quiet life until his death in [[Hove]], [[Sussex]], 22 days after that of his wife.<ref name=adb/> He was succeeded in the barony by his son, Thomas Denman, 4th Baron Denman.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] | before=[[Victor Spencer, 1st Viscount Churchill|The Viscount Churchill]] | after=[[Richard Herschell, 2nd Baron Herschell|The Lord Herschell]] | years=1905\u20131907}}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[William Lygon, 7th Earl Beauchamp|The Earl Beauchamp]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Captain of the Gentlemen-at-Arms]]\n       | years  = 1907\u20131911 }}\n{{s-aft| rows   = 2 | after  = [[Edward Arthur Colebrooke, 1st Baron Colebrooke|The Lord Colebrooke]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Thomas Lister, 4th Baron Ribblesdale|The Lord Ribblesdale]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Government Chief Whip]] in the [[House of Lords]]\n       | years  = 1907\u20131911 }}\n\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | years=1911\u20131914 | title=[[Governor-General of Australia]] | before=[[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|The Earl of Dudley]] | after=[[Ronald Munro Ferguson, 1st Viscount Novar|Sir Ronald Munro Ferguson]]}}\n\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Denman]] | before=[[Thomas Aitchison-Denman, 2nd Baron Denman|Thomas Aitchison-Denman]] | after=[[Thomas Denman, 4th Baron Denman|Thomas Denman]] | years=1894\u20131954}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors-General of Australia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denman, Thomas Denman, 3rd Baron}}\n[[Category:Governors-General of Australia]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of the Order of St Michael and St George]]\n[[Category:Knights Commander of the Royal Victorian Order]]\n[[Category:Liberal Party (UK) Lords-in-Waiting]]\n[[Category:1874 births]]\n[[Category:1954 deaths]]\n[[Category:Honourable Corps of Gentlemen at Arms]]\n[[Category:Middlesex Yeomanry officers]]\n[[Category:Members of the Privy Council of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Denman family]]\n[[Category:Politicians awarded knighthoods]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=April 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}}\n{{Infobox Governor-General\n| honorific-prefix = [[The Right Honourable]]\n|name = The Lord Denman\n| honorific-suffix = {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=|GCMG|KCVO|PC}}\n|image=Lord Denman.jpg\n|order=5th\n|office=Governor-General of Australia\n|term_start=31 July 1911\n|term_end=18 May 1914\n|monarch=[[George V]]\n|primeminister    = [[Andrew Fisher]]<br/>[[Joseph Cook]]\n|predecessor=[[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|Lord Dudley]]\n|successor=[[Ronald Munro Ferguson, 1st Viscount Novar|Sir Ronald Munro Ferguson]]\n|birth_date={{birth date|1874|11|16|df=y}}\n|birth_place=[[London]], England\n|death_date={{death date and age|1954|6|24|1874|11|16|df=y}}\n|death_place=[[Hove]], [[Sussex]], England\n|spouse={{Marriage|[[Gertrude Denman, Baroness Denman|Gertrude Pearson]]|1913|1954|reason=her death}}\n}}\n\n'''Thomas Denman, 3rd Baron Denman''', {{postnominals|country=GBR|size=100%|sep=,|GCMG|KCVO|PC}} (16 November 1874 \u2013 24 June 1954), was a British aristocrat and politician who served as the [[List of Governors-General of Australia|fifth Governor-General of Australia]], in office from 1911 to 1914.\n\nDenman was born into the English nobility, inheriting his title at the age of 19 from a great-uncle. He attended the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]], and served in the [[Second Boer War]]. Denman sat with the [[Liberal Party (UK)|Liberal Party]] in the [[House of Lords]], and was made a [[Lord-in-waiting]] in 1905 and [[Chief Whip of the Liberal Democrats#Liberal Party|Chief Whip]] in 1907. He was appointed to the governor-generalship at the age of 36, and remains the youngest person to have held the position. Denman and his young family were immensely popular with the general public, and he enjoyed friendly relations with Prime Minister [[Andrew Fisher]], with whom he shared many similar political opinions. However, he suffered from ill health and returned to England after less than three years as governor-general. Denman never again held public office, but remained active in the House of Lords and briefly commanded a unit in the First World War.\n\n==Early life and military career==\nDenman was born in [[London]] on 16 November 1874, the son of Richard Denman and the former Helen Mary McMicking. His father was the grandson of [[Thomas Denman, 1st Baron Denman]], who was [[Lord Chief Justice of England and Wales|Lord Chief Justice]] from 1832 to 1850. Denman was the second of three children, and the oldest son. His younger brother, [[Richard Denman|Sir Richard Denman]], was also a Liberal Party politician.<ref>{{cite web|title=Thomas Denman, 3rd Baron Denman of Dovedale|url=http://www.thepeerage.com/p13233.htm#i132327|publisher=thepeerage.com|accessdate=5 April 2011|date=6 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nDenman's parents divorced in 1878. His father did not remarry, and died in 1883 when his son was eight.<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p2357.htm#i23562 Hon. Richard Denman]</ref> However, his mother remarried twice \u2013 in 1879 to James Walker (annulled due to desertion), and then in 1888 to [[Henry Primrose]] (a civil servant and cousin of [[Archibald Primrose, 5th Earl of Rosebery|Lord Rosebery]]).<ref>[http://www.thepeerage.com/p2951.htm Helen Mary McMicking]</ref>\n\nIn 1894, aged 19, Denman succeeded [[Thomas Aitchison-Denman, 2nd Baron Denman|his great-uncle]] as Baron Denman; he took his seat in the [[House of Lords]] on his 21st birthday. He intended a military career and was a graduate of the [[Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]. Denman began his career in the [[Royal Scots]], where he was promoted to [[Lieutenant (British Army and Royal Marines)|lieutenant]] on 4 March 1896, but resigned in May 1899 and was placed in the Reserve. Returning to active service following the outbreak of the [[Second Boer War]], he was on 3 February 1900 commissioned as a lieutenant of the 11th Battalion, [[Imperial Yeomanry]],<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27160 |page=692 |date=2 February 1900}}</ref> and left [[Liverpool]] for [[South Africa]] on the [[SS Cymric|SS ''Cymric'']] in March 1900.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The War - Embarcation of Troops|day_of_week=Thursday |date=1 March 1900 |page_number=7 |issue=36078| }}</ref> He was promoted to [[Captain (BARM)|captain]] in the battalion on 18 July 1900, and the following year was appointed a captain in the [[Middlesex Yeomanry|Middlesex (Duke of Cambridge's Hussars) Imperial Yeomanry]], followed by a promotion to [[Major (British Army)|major]] on 30 April 1902.<ref>{{London Gazette| issue=27429 |page=2866 |date=29 April 1902}}</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nDenman had little money until 1903, when he married [[Gertrude Denman, Baroness Denman|Gertrude Pearson]], daughter of the wealthy industrialist [[Weetman Pearson, 1st Viscount Cowdray|Weetman Pearson]] (later Viscount Cowdray). He was then able to devote his time to public life and served in the [[Liberal Government 1905-1915|Liberal administrations]] of Sir [[Henry Campbell-Bannerman]] and [[H. H. Asquith]] as a [[Lord-in-waiting]] (government whip in the House of Lords) from 1905 to 1907 and as [[Captain of the Honourable Corps of Gentlemen-at-Arms]] (government chief whip in the House of Lords) between 1907 and 1911. He was sworn of the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]] in 1907.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28050 |date=13 August 1907 |page=5523}}</ref> In 1909, he was appointed to the [[Royal Victorian Order]] as a Knight Commander.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28251 |date=17 May 1909 |page=3753 |supp=y}}</ref> In 1911, [[Lewis Harcourt, 1st Viscount Harcourt|Lord Harcourt]], the [[Secretary of State for the Colonies|Colonial Secretary]], offered Denman the post of [[Governor-General of Australia]],<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28483 |date=7 April 1911 |page=2802}}</ref> apparently to get him out of domestic politics.<ref name=adb>{{Australian Dictionary of Biography |last= Cunneen |first= Chris |year=1981 |id=A080304b |title= Denman, Thomas [Baron Denman] (1874\u20131954) |accessdate=30 April 2008 }}</ref> In the [[1911 Coronation Honours]], Lord Denman was appointed to the [[Order of St Michael and St George]] as a Knight Grand Cross.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=28505 |date=16 June 1911 |page=4593 |supp=y}}</ref>\n\n==Governor-General==\n[[Image:Aussie pm Andrew Fisher cropped from naming of Canberra.JPG|left|thumb|Denman, to the left of [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] Prime Minister [[Andrew Fisher]], at the naming of [[Canberra]] in 1913.]]\n[[File:Laying of the foundation stone of the Commencement Column, Canberra.jpg|left|thumb|Lord and Lady Denman, [[King O'Malley]] and Andrew Fisher at the official ceremony on Capitol Hill to mark the commencement of work on the city of Canberra, 12 March 1913]]\n[[File:The cadets being inspected by the Governor-General 12 March 1913.jpg|thumb|The cadets being inspected by the Governor-General on 12 March 1913, at the Canberra naming ceremony]]\nThe Denmans arrived in Melbourne on 31 July 1911.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://adb.anu.edu.au/biography/denman-thomas-5956|title = Denman, Thomas (1874\u20131954)|date = 1981|accessdate = 1 April 2015|website = Australian Dictionary of Biography|publisher = Melbourne University Press|last = Cunneen|first = Chris}}</ref> They found [[Andrew Fisher]]'s [[Australian Labor Party|Labor]] government firmly in control. As the most politically liberal Governor-General yet appointed, he got on well with the Labor ministers, and his modesty and generosity with his father-in-law's money made him popular with the public.  In October 1912, the [[Premiers of New South Wales|New South Wales Premier]], [[James McGowen]] \"evicted\" him from [[Government House, Sydney]]. On 12 March 1913, he inaugurated the site of the future national capital and Lady Denman formally announced its name, [[Canberra]].<ref name=adb/> On 12 March 2013, his great-nephew, the 6th Baron Denman and his wife attended celebrations in Canberra commemorating the centenary of the naming of the city.<ref>[http://www.canberratimes.com.au/act-news/100-years-on-the-denmans-pay-visit-to-scene-of-ancestors-public-office-20130310-2fukr.html ''Canberra Times'', 11 March 2013]</ref>\n\nBut Denman found that he had less real political influence than any previous Governor-General. As Australia, along with the other [[dominion]]s, achieved political maturity, its Prime Minister communicated directly with his British counterpart, cutting the Colonial Secretary and the Governor-General out of the loop. The appointment of an Australian High Commissioner in London further reduced the Governor-General's diplomatic role.\n\nIn May 1913 the Labor government was unexpectedly defeated at a [[1913 Australian federal election|general election]] by [[Joseph Cook]]'s [[Commonwealth Liberal Party|Liberals]]. But Labor retained control of the [[Australian Senate|Senate]] and was determined to frustrate Cook's government at every turn. By early 1914 it was clear that a [[constitutional crisis]] was developing.  Denman was in poor health{{mdash}}that he was allergic to Australia's national flower, the wattle, did not help{{mdash}}and his marriage was suffering from his wife's unhappiness at being so far from home. He felt he lacked the strength to deal with the political situation, and in May 1914 he resigned.<ref name=adb/>\n\nThe [[Denman Glacier]] in eastern [[Antarctica]] was named after Denman by [[Sir Douglas Mawson]]. It had been discovered by the [[Australasian Antarctic Expedition]] of 1911-14.\n\n==Later years==\nWith the outbreak of the [[World War I|Great War]], Denman commanded a [[Yeomanry]] regiment from 1914 until 1915. He was appointed [[Colonel_(United_Kingdom)#Ceremonial_usage|Honorary Colonel]] of the [[2nd Cavalry Divisional Signals (Middlesex Yeomanry)]] on 11 April 1923.<ref>''Army List''.</ref> He remained loyal to [[H. H. Asquith|Asquith]] and the Liberals and so did not hold office again, leading a quiet life until his death in [[Hove]], [[Sussex]], 22 days after that of his wife.<ref name=adb/> He was succeeded in the barony by his son, Thomas Denman, 4th Baron Denman.\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Lord-in-waiting]] | before=[[Victor Spencer, 1st Viscount Churchill|The Viscount Churchill]] | after=[[Richard Herschell, 2nd Baron Herschell|The Lord Herschell]] | years=1905\u20131907}}\n\n{{s-bef| before = [[William Lygon, 7th Earl Beauchamp|The Earl Beauchamp]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Captain of the Gentlemen-at-Arms]]\n       | years  = 1907\u20131911 }}\n{{s-aft| rows   = 2 | after  = [[Edward Arthur Colebrooke, 1st Baron Colebrooke|The Lord Colebrooke]] }}\n{{s-bef| before = [[Thomas Lister, 4th Baron Ribblesdale|The Lord Ribblesdale]] }}\n{{s-ttl| title  = [[Government Chief Whip]] in the [[House of Lords]]\n       | years  = 1907\u20131911 }}\n\n{{s-gov}}\n{{succession box | years=1911\u20131914 | title=[[Governor-General of Australia]] | before=[[William Ward, 2nd Earl of Dudley|The Earl of Dudley]] | after=[[Ronald Munro Ferguson, 1st Viscount Novar|Sir Ronald Munro Ferguson]]}}\n\n{{s-reg|uk}}\n{{succession box | title=[[Baron Denman]] | before=[[Thomas Aitchison-Denman, 2nd Baron Denman|Thomas Aitchison-Denman]] | after=[[Thomas Denman, 4th Baron Denman|Thomas Denman]] | years=1894\u20131954}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors-General of Australia}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Denman, Thomas Denman, 3rd Baron}}\n[[Category:Governors-General of Australia]]\n[[Category:Barons in the Peerage of the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Graduates of the Royal Military College, Sandhurst]]\n[[Category:Knights Grand Cross of